          <figure class="cover">
            <img src={cover} alt="Graffiti wall with the words Equality, Kindness, Truth" loading="eager" />
          </figure>
        )}
      </header>

      <article class="content">
        <p>For most of my life, I lived for other people. I did what was expected of me, what kept other people happy, what avoided rocking the boat. Especially when it came to my mother ‚Äî a woman who thrived on control, criticism, and reminding me that my worth was conditional.</p>
        <p>And when you live like that long enough, you stop naming your feelings. You stop asking yourself, <em>Why am I upset?</em> or <em>Why does this hurt me?</em> Instead, it all boils down to one big emotion: anger. And anger was the only language I knew.</p>
        <p>But here‚Äôs the problem: anger wasn‚Äôt working. It didn‚Äôt solve anything. It didn‚Äôt make me feel better. It didn‚Äôt change the systems, the people, or the injustices that pissed me off in the first place. And the longer I pretended it was working, the more insane I felt ‚Äî repeating the same explosion over and over, expecting a different result.</p>

        <h2>üö™ Healing Made Me Stop and Ask Why</h2>
        <p>When I started my healing journey, I had to relearn how to feel. And not just feel ‚Äî but name those feelings. <strong>This is grief. This is disappointment. This is shame. This is injustice.</strong></p>
        <p>Because once I could name the emotion, I could finally ask: <em>Why am I feeling this way? What is this pointing to?</em></p>
        <p>That‚Äôs when things started to shift.</p>
        <p>I realized I can‚Äôt control my emotions (they‚Äôre going to come, like waves), but I can control my actions. I can control how I show up to those emotions. Do I lash out? Do I shut down? Or do I take a breath, ask why, and make a different choice?</p>

        <h2>‚ö° Anger Is a Value Misaligned</h2>
        <p>Here‚Äôs what I‚Äôve learned: most of my anger comes from something happening that doesn‚Äôt align with my values.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Lack of transparency.</li>
          <li>Sneaky, manipulative systems.</li>
          <li>People taking advantage of those who are already disadvantaged.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Nothing gets me more fired up than that. And when I notice my blood boiling, nine times out of ten, it‚Äôs because something is violating those values.</p>
        <p>That‚Äôs why I lose my shit when I‚Äôm stuck in an endless loop with State Farm or Verizon, trying to get what I already paid for. Or when I sat in a hospital bed and they tried to prescribe me one of the two medications I‚Äôm literally allergic to ‚Äî even though it‚Äôs right there in my chart. If I wasn‚Äôt my own advocate, I could‚Äôve died.</p>
        <p>This is why I now pay extra out of pocket for a direct primary care doctor, <strong>Dr. Wendy Molaska</strong>. Because with her, I don‚Äôt have to beg someone to remember my forty-three years of medical history. I can text her pictures at 5:17am and she actually knows my story. That‚Äôs what healthcare should look like.</p>
        <p>Same with <strong>Anker</strong>, the company behind my Soundcore earbuds. Their customer service team responded to my warranty claim within one business day, followed up when I missed their email, and shipped me a replacement with no hoops, no hassle, no gaslighting. Compare that to the corporate giants who only seem to respond when you threaten legal action or blast them on social media. Night and day.</p>

        <h2>üí£ The Bigger Picture</h2>
        <p>And then there‚Äôs the world around us. Every day, it feels like one more headline breaks me open:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Another school shooting.</li>
          <li>Another person killed while the so-called ‚Äúparty of American values‚Äù clutches their pearls in shock‚Äîafter cheering ‚Äúguns for all.‚Äù</li>
          <li>Another family crying out for mental health support that doesn‚Äôt exist because the system is already at capacity.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>We are living in a country where everyone is exhausted, overworked, beaten down‚Äîand the only time people seem to get results is when they threaten, scream, or sue.</p>
        <p>No wonder we‚Äôre all angry. But anger alone isn‚Äôt moving the needle.</p>

        <h2>‚ú® Choosing Differently</h2>
        <p>I‚Äôm not saying I roll over now. Absolutely not. I still stand my ground. I still call out bullshit when I see it. But I do it differently now.</p>
        <p>I approach my anger with curiosity instead of letting it consume me. I ask: <em>What value of mine is being stepped on? What‚Äôs the real injustice here? How can I push back in a way that doesn‚Äôt destroy me in the process?</em></p>
        <p>That doesn‚Äôt mean I‚Äôm soft. It means I‚Äôm strategic. I‚Äôm compassionate. I‚Äôm building bridges where they can be built, and drawing hard lines where they can‚Äôt.</p>
        <p>Because here‚Äôs the truth: <strong>kindness is not weakness. Kindness rules the day.</strong> Fighting for what‚Äôs right doesn‚Äôt mean screaming‚Äîit means choosing actions that align with your values, even when the world doesn‚Äôt.</p>

        <h2>üìñ Where to Begin</h2>
        <p>If this all feels overwhelming and you‚Äôre wondering where to even start, I‚Äôll tell you what has helped me: <strong>The Let Them Theory</strong>, popularized by Mel Robbins. By now, you‚Äôve probably heard about it. Maybe you‚Äôve even bought the book because 30498023 other people recommended it and it‚Äôs been sitting on your nightstand, silently judging you.</p>
        <p>Here‚Äôs the gist: you can‚Äôt control other people. You can‚Äôt control their actions, their emotions, their choices. All you can control is your own response. Let them do what they‚Äôre going to do‚Äîand then choose how you will act in alignment with your own peace and values.</p>
        <p>It‚Äôs not rolling over. It‚Äôs refusing to carry responsibility that isn‚Äôt yours. It‚Äôs freedom.</p>
        <p>üëâ If you want a place to start, read her book. Seriously. Check out <a href="https://www.melrobbins.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Mel Robbins‚Äô website here</a>.</p>

        <h2>üå± Why I‚Äôm Sharing This</h2>
        <p>I‚Äôm sharing this because I know I‚Äôm not the only one who‚Äôs tired. I know I‚Äôm not the only one who‚Äôs woken up every morning for the last four years feeling disheartened by the world.</p>
        <p>And I want you to hear this:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>You‚Äôre not crazy for feeling angry.</li>
          <li>You‚Äôre not weak for wanting peace.</li>
          <li>You don‚Äôt have to burn your whole life down to stand for your values.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>You only need to start by naming your feelings, asking why, and then choosing differently.</p>
        <p>That‚Äôs how we turn anger into alignment. That‚Äôs how we build a kinder world. That‚Äôs how we make the whole damn place shimmer.</p>

        <footer class="foot">
          <div>‚Äî Parker</div>
          <nav class="share" aria-label="Share this post">
            <button class="btn" id="copyLinkBtn" type="button">Copy Link</button>
            <a class="btn" id="fbShare" href="#" rel="noopener">Share on Facebook</a>
            <a class="btn" href="/blog/">Back to Blog</a>
          </nav>
        </footer>
      </article>
    </main>

    <div id="toast" role="status" aria-live="polite" aria-atomic="true">Link copied ‚ú®</div>

    <script type="module">
      const url = new URL(window.location.href);
      const copyBtn = document.getElementById("copyLinkBtn");
      const fbA = document.getElementById("fbShare");
      const toast = document.getElementById("toast");

      const fbShareUrl = new URL("https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php");
      fbShareUrl.searchParams.set("u", url.href);
      fbA.href = fbShareUrl.toString();

      copyBtn?.addEventListener("click", async () => {
        try {
          if (navigator.clipboard?.writeText) {
            await navigator.clipboard.writeText(url.href);
          } else {
            const ta = document.createElement("textarea");
            ta.value = url.href;
            document.body.appendChild(ta);
            ta.select();
            document.execCommand("copy");
            ta.remove();
          }
          toast.classList.add("show");
          setTimeout(() => toast.classList.remove("show"), 1400);
        } catch {}
      });
    </script>
  </body>
</html>
